{{Otheruses||The similarly named castle in [[Gifu Prefecture]]'s [[Ena City]]|{{ill|Ōi Castle (Mino Province)|ja|大井城 (美濃国)|12=draft|12=draft}}}} {{Infobox Japanese castle | name = Ōi Castle | pref = Nagano Prefecture | alias = Ishinarabi Castle, Ōjō, Kuroiwa Castle | structure = Hirayama-style castle | tower_struct = | builders = {{ill|Ōi Tomomitsu|ja|大井朝光|12=draft|12=draft}}? | build_year = [[Jōkyū]] 3 (1221) | rulers = {{ill|Ōi Mitsunaga|ja|大井光長|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōi Chikayuki|ja|大井朝行|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōi Mitsusaka|ja|大井光栄|lt=Ōi Mitsunaga (Mitsusaka)|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōi Mitsunori|ja|大井光矩|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōi Mochimitsu|ja|大井持光|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōi Awa-maru|ja|大井安房丸|12=draft|12=draft}}, among others | destroyed_year = [[Bunmei (era)|Bunmei]] 16 (1484) | remains = Kuruwa (enclosures) | cultural_asset = Nagano Prefecture Historic Site<ref>{{Cite web|title=Prefectural Historic Sites|url=http://www.pref.nagano.lg.jp/kyoiku/bunsho/bunka/rekishi/documents/13ken-siseki.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Nagano Prefecture|date=2016-02-25|accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref> | location=|latd=36|latm=16|lats=29.8 | longd=138|longm=28|longs=55.9 | map=Japan Nagano | label=Ōi Castle | latitude_deg=36|latitude_min=16|latitude_sec=29.8 | longitude_deg=138|longitude_min=28|longitude_sec=55.9 | icon=Japanese castle ruins | label_position=bottom }}
'''Ōi Castle''' (大井城, ''Ōi-jō'') was a [[Japanese castle]] located in [[Iwamurada]], [[Saku City]], [[Nagano Prefecture]]. It is a Nagano Prefecture-designated [[Historic Site]] and was the seat of the {{ill|Ōi clan (Shinano Province)|ja|信濃大井氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, who served as deputies to the [[Governor of Shinano Province]]. The castle was also known as '''Iwamurada Residence''' (岩村田館).
== History ==
Ōi Castle was located in northeastern Saku City, along the [[Yukawa River (Nagano)|Yukawa]]'s cliffs. It consisted of three fortifications: Ishinarabi Castle (石並城), Ōjō (王城), and Kuroiwa Castle (黒岩城). According to the ''[[Shirin Danzō]]'', the castle was established by {{ill|Ōi Tomomitsu|ja|大井朝光|12=draft|12=draft}}, the progenitor of the {{ill|Ōi clan (Shinano Province)|ja|信濃大井氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, a branch of the [[Seiwa Genji]] descending from {{ill|Ogasawara Nagachika|ja|小笠原長清|12=draft|12=draft}}. From its founding in [[Jōkyū]] 3 (1221) until its fall in [[Bunmei (era)|Bunmei]] 16 (1484), the Ōi clan controlled northeastern Saku District from this base.
In [[Kōan (era)|Kōan]] 2 (1279), the second lord {{ill|Ōi Mitsunaga|ja|大井光長|12=draft|12=draft}} donated a temple bell to the {{ill|Shinzenkō-ji|ja|新善光寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in [[Naruse]], Saku. The exact location of the manor depicted in the ''Illustrated Biography of Ippen'' remains uncertain.
During the [[Kemmu Restoration]] in [[Kemmu (era)|Kemmu]] 2 (1335), the fourth lord {{ill|Ōi Chikayuki|ja|大井朝行|12=draft|12=draft}} supported the {{ill|Ashikaga clan|ja|足利氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, joining the Northern Court. He clashed with the Southern Court forces, including {{ill|Kutsuna Shigekiyo|ja|忽那重清|12=draft|12=draft}}, who were advancing toward [[Kamakura]] along the Eastern Mountain Road. Despite several days of fierce resistance, the castle eventually fell, as recorded in documents like ''Battle of Ōi Manor'' and ''Kutsuna Papers''.
The castle was later rebuilt. The fifth lord, {{ill|Ōi Mitsusaka|ja|大井光栄|lt=Ōi Mitsunaga (Mitsusaka)|12=draft|12=draft}}, served as Deputy Governor of Shinano Province. His son, the sixth lord {{ill|Ōi Mitsunori|ja|大井光矩|12=draft|12=draft}}, mediated during the [[Ōtō Rebellion]] in [[Ōei]] 7 (1400), aiding the defeated {{ill|Ogasawara Nagahide|ja|小笠原長秀|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Under the seventh lord {{ill|Ōi Mochimitsu|ja|大井持光|12=draft|12=draft}}, the clan reached its zenith. The Ōi castle town flourished, with over 6,000 households, surpassing the provincial capital ([[Matsumoto City|Matsumoto]]). Mochimitsu's reign saw vast territorial control, including 60,000 ''koku'' in northern Saku and estates in [[Kōzuke Province|Kōzuke]] and [[Musashi Province|Musashi]]. He reportedly led 1,000 troops to Kyoto.
In [[Eikyō]] 10 (1438), Mochimitsu sheltered {{ill|Eijū ōmaru|ja|永寿王丸|12=draft|12=draft}}, the orphaned son of [[Ashikaga Mochiuji]], at {{ill|An'yō-ji|ja|安養寺 (佐久市)|12=draft|12=draft}} during the [[Eikyō Rebellion]].
Subsequent lords faced difficulties. In [[Bunmei (era)|Bunmei]] 16 (1484), {{ill|Murakami Masakiyo|ja|村上政清|12=draft|12=draft}} attacked Ōi Castle, which was set ablaze, marking the end of the Ōi main family’s 260-year rule.
Though the main line perished, branches like the {{ill|Iwao clan|ja|岩尾氏|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Aiki clan|ja|相木氏|12=draft|12=draft}} persisted. {{ill|Ōi Genkei|ja|大井玄慶|12=draft|12=draft}} inherited the castle but was ousted by [[Takeda Shingen]] in [[Tenbun]] 12 (1543). Later, during the [[Tenshō]] era, {{ill|Ōi Gakujo|ja|大井雅楽助|12=draft|12=draft}} surrendered the castle to {{ill|Yoda Nobushige|ja|依田信蕃|12=draft|12=draft}}, a retainer of [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]].
Today, little remains of the castle. The main enclosure is a public park, home to a giant [[zelkova]] designated a prefectural natural monument<ref>{{Cite web|title=Prefectural Natural Monuments|url=http://www.pref.nagano.lg.jp/kyoiku/bunsho/bunka/rekishi/documents/15ken-tennenkinenbutu.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Nagano Prefecture|date=2016-02-25|accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref>.
